title: For Sale/Trade:  DPMS AR15 Tactical with Free Floating Rail
postcontent:
*Kicked it down to $1200, I'm taking a big loss but I really want to start my new project. Also if you don't want the Fortis handguard I'll sell without for $1,000* I'm selling my DPMS Oracle AR15 that I have put a LOT into. It's been an amazing rifle that has worked flawlessly. I love the way it's setup and I love the Fortis Rev 12" Free Floating Rail. Not one FTF of any kind, it's ran everything perfectly. I shoot 90% of the time at 50 yards(150ft) and the other 10% from 7 yards to 25 yards. It drives center every single time. All the work was done professionally at Hawk Tech Arms, everything on it was put on buy them. Basically I want to dig deaper into the AR world, try other brands, and setup another AR the way I want. I'm in the Army and M4's have always been my thing, that being said I would have no problem putting my life on this DPMS. It has honestly ran like a dream. I just want to get out of if what I've put in so I can move one and start another build, it's my new hobby :) The EoTech 517 does NOT come with the AR, that is my baby and will go on every build i run. The Pmag doesn't go either. I would trade for the right items. If you have an ACR that maybe you're just not a fan of I will trade straight across for it, I love that platform and would love more time behind it. If an AR15 that maybe you don't have time to configure your way, I would consider depending on the brand, specs, condition, and depending on price point cash to come with it. You never know give me a line. Lot of people bash DPMS but most have never owned one, a lot of Law Enforcement Agencies use DPMS including SWAT teams. I'm pretty confident this AR15 will out live me. I would keep it but I can't afford to have multiple projects. Again I will trade for an ACR, I'll even throw $200 cash on top of the trade or OBO depending on model. I have seen a lot of people dislike the ACR and want to go back to an AR, I've even seen it right here on Armslist. If maybe you want to go back to an AR platform this is an amazing AR that's setup well, good condition, and accurate. There are people out there that put there lives on DPMS every day and so would I. I just want to play with an ACR or start a new project.

It's only had maybe 600 rounds through it and it's been cleaned and oiled often and after every use. Everything listed is what I've done too it. It had a stupid gas block on it that didn't even align to the receiver and a commercial buffer tube which makes it harder to find good stocks for it. It's all been changed. Also it comes with the original box, paperwork, and magazine. The new Magpul AFG1 and Stock boxes will be included. I have shot both 5.56 and .223 different grains and loads of each, all factory ammo. it runs everything flawlessly. I personally loved the PMC 5.56 62gr X-tac LAP.

title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec KSG High Cap 14 round Bullpup Tactical
postcontent:
The KSG comes with the Magpul RVG vertical grip, sling, box, paperwork and lock.

The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".

This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.



The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.



The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

title: For Sale:  1951 Beretta SxS, Model 408, 12 ga
postcontent:
Beretta SxS, Model 408, 12 ga 
- 26 3/4 inch or 68 centimeter long barrels, choked Mod. and Full. It has a sliding rod, hidden third fastener, aticulated front trigger, a button forend release, sling swivels, and a sunken rib known in Italy as a St. Eitenne or ulta light rib. The gun weighs six pound eight ounces. I know it is very rare, especially in the U.S. The lady from Beretta told me that is was never intended for export. 
  This shotgun  is very interesting b/c instead of using a greener cross bolt, there is a bolt that slides forward between the barrels from the breach face.  This is a very similar system that was used by the Snipe and the later 686/687 models. 

It is designed for field use.  It has extractors, not ejectors. A classic vintage field Beretta side-by-side,  due to it not being offered in the US and something of collectors item I am asking $2k for it.  Barrels have Ausonia Electric Steel inscribed on them & made in Italy.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson U.S. MODEL 1917 .45 DA Revolver
postcontent:
What I have is an S&W .45 Hand Ejector Model 1917 U.S. Army service revolver.

This revolver is in very good condition for a pistol that is approaching 100 years old. The mechanism works like new. This gun has it's original bluing which survives about 85%-90%. It has the standard 5-1/2" barrel for the Model 1917's, and fixed sights. Lanyard ring on butt of the gun. This is a used gun from the war and there are some nicks and scrapes from use. The bore is excellent, no rust or pitting. The rifling is strong and crisp.

This is a very early gun which has the smooth walnut grips and the serial number is also penciled in on the inside of the wood grips. Right side of barrel is marked S.&W. D.A. 45 and the bottom is marked "UNITED STATES PROPERTY". The name and patent dates are on top of the barrel. Bottom of butt marked U.S. ARMY MODEL 1917 with serial No. 898xx. The Serial number is repeated on the barrel and cylinder face. flaming bomb is near the hammer on the top left of the frame. The early (WWI) flaming bomb ordnance stamp is found on the upper left side of the frame next to the hammer.

title: For Sale:  GGG Precision 5.56x45mm 1,000 Round Wire Sealed M2A1 Case
postcontent:
The real world implications for those who choose GGG ammunition is smaller, tighter, more precise and more accurate groups that are typically more than twice as good as baseline NATO ball ammunition specifications. For those shooters who expect the best, GGG is the ammunition of choice.

“The Lithuanian NATO (GGG) is not just good but great brass. I would swear it was made by Lapua or Lapua at least set up their plant. Necks annealed, very uniform in weight, slightly smaller internal capacity than Lake City, and capable of extraordinary accuracy once you take the crimp out of the primer pocket. In fact, the NATO load itself is the most accurate military ball I have seen” -  Sniper Hide Forum

“I've used the Lithuanian ammo and found it to be the highest quality of any M80 type ammo I've used. Accuracy was superior to WCC and LC M80 ammo that I've used. The brass is good quality also” - Sniper Hide Forum

“It's awesome ammo!! - I've got several cases & wish i had more... it's accurate, clean shooting & boxer primed” - M14forum.com

“The GGG brass is fantastic! Its loads great and is a high quality grade of brass too, nice primer pockets to[…] the brass alone is worth it” -M14forum.com

“[GGG] seems to be abnormally accurate, and the brass abnormally good for reloading” - M4carbine.net

“The GGG stuff is something I keep hearing about” - AR15.com

Unlike most other ‘NATO’ ammunition on the market GGG GP21 and GP11 is new production; not old surplus, product overrun or ‘NATO like’ imitations. GGG GP21 and GP11 are 100% authentic military ammunition exceeding all STANAG and MOPI requirements. ADINT and GGG manufacture and qualify GGG GP21 and GP11 ammunition to the same rigorous standards whether the end user is the US commercial market or a front line military combat unit. GGG and ADINT spare no expenses in the manufacturing process using only the highest grade of brass with deep annealing that is excellent for reloading. The military grade boxer primers are non-corrosive, non-mercuric and exceed all sensitivity requirements for combat use. A high quality double base smokeless propellant is used. The full metal jackets are made from tombac. The case mouth and case primer joint have a waterproof sealing. The M2A1 cases are sealed with a full rubber gasket. There is also a wire and pressed stamp lock around the hinge which must be cut to open. As a result of both the quality manufacturing and the packaging, when stored in this fashion, GGG NATO ammunition has a minimum shelf life of no less than 20 years. GGG NATO qualified ammunition far exceeds the benchmark and typical performance of other NATO ammunition.

GGG’s use of the highest quality materials and attention to detail are differences shooters notice downrange. Old surplus or ‘knock-off’ military ammunition that never pass NATO qualification testing is simply not a valid comparison for GGG ammunition. GGG GP21 and GP11 is redefining the way shooters are thinking about military ball ammunition.
